summary:
Okay so here’s my take on that deleted Captain Marvel scene:
From what I gather, yeah, he was being creepy, but no, a hero...
body:
Okay so here’s my take on that deleted Captain Marvel scene:

From what I gather, yeah, he was being creepy, but no, a hero wouldn’t have robbed him. HOWEVER, this early on in the film, I don’t consider Captain Marvel a hero yet. She’s still working (albeit unwittingly) with the “bad guys,” and she’s in the midst of her origin story. The whole point is that she has character development and GROWTH. She’s not supposed to already be a flawless hero.

Think of it this way: People have given Tony Stark a lot of shit for the way he started out in the first film, so why is he not being brought up now as a comparison (this is coming from a major tony lover, so tony antis, please don’t interact)?

In the first Spider-Man film, Peter Parker allows a robber to escape because he felt wronged, leading to his uncle’s murder (we’re ignoring Spider-Man 3 because that mess of webs need not be acknowledged as canon. EVER.).

In the first Thor movie, Thor acts like a real dick and has to work up to being worthy of wielding Milojnir. He isn’t magically a great, selfless hero.

So yeah, what she did in that scene shouldn’t be praised as “feminist” or as a good thing to do, but I hardly think that should be used to call her a villain. Origin stories are meant for growth. Had this been a scene in Endgame, it’d be a different story. But this was in the beginning of her introduction, when she’s still learning how to be a good person.

As a side-note, let’s also not forget that she’s essentially been an alien/lost her memories, and could be going based off of the social customs she was taught with the Kree (I mean, they’re assholes, so I wouldn’t put it past them to act like that).

summary: ooh for the are we the strongest, how about the Avengers going on a karaoke? Or maybe Carol like trying to teach them Kree...
question: ooh for the are we the strongest, how about the Avengers going on a karaoke? Or maybe Carol like trying to teach them Kree Glyphs? You can pick whatever you want to write a blurb for😊. Thank you so much, sweets! Have a great day!🎉
answer:
loved this idea thank you

Are We the Strongest?

How on Earth, nay, how in the galaxies that Tony was just finding out about did Pepper convince him to do this? He stood outside the bar and listened to the unmistakable aggressive shout of Rocket. Panic. His breathing became shallow. Steve was in there. Steve who would find some new way to torture him without even realising. Why was he here?

“You come here often?” A very familiar, and comfortably welcome, voice made him spin around.

“Sorry to disappoint, but only when my wife forces me too.” He grunts as Carol pulls him into her chest a little too used to the super strength she’d been using on other planets.

“I’ll protect you, little pensioner.” She cooed into his ear as he rolled his eyes.

“I think I preferred old softie.” He grumbled, struggling out of her grip.

“Ironpensioner it is.” She grinned, strutting into the bar.

“Carol, wait.” He grabbed her sleeve and pulled her back into the cold night air. “I can’t go back in there yet.”

“He had it coming. If he wants to say anything about it, he can say it to me first.” She concluded as she dragged him inside.

“God, I wish you were the first captain I met.” Tony stumbled in behind her and led her to the bar.

“Two beers.” She ordered, catching Tony’s disgruntled look out of the corner of her eye. “We’re doing karaoke, so I need you drunk.”

“Remind me, why am I friends with you again?” He asked, taking the beer from her hands and walking towards the ragtag table of mismatched weirdos.

“Because I’m amazing.” She sung, slinging an arm around Nat.

“Hey, guys.” The spy beamed at them.

“Hi. Heard you’ve done good with keeping the universe safe. Always knew you should have been the one in charge.” Tony tried not to glance at Steve, but his volume was louder than it needed to be and the two women smirked behind their drinks. “Cap.”

“Tony. It’s nice to see you.” Steve nodded at him.

“Oh, I was talking to Carol.” He snickered. “Bruce! Long time no see!”

After Tony had greeted everyone and felt comfortable with the amount of teasing he’d done to Steve, Carol pulled him up to the karaoke machine.

“What song do we want?” She flipped through the pages of the songbook. “Nat did Killer Queen, as suggested by you, so no Queen songs. Although, Rocket’s one whiskey away from doing Another One Bites the Dust.”

“AC/DC Highway to Hell.” He answered confidently.

“If we’re doing a rock band, we do the superior one: Guns ‘N’ Roses.” Tony laughed, humourless and cold.

“I’m not gonna get into this because I am way to drunk, so Sweet Child of Mine or I walk.” He exclaimed, swinging his beer around.

“Alright, didn’t know you were so bad with your liquor.” The song began to play and Tony handed his phone to Steve.

“Film it for Morgan. For Morgan because she’s that Sweet Child of Mine.” He demanded, hips swaying as he grabbed his mic.

“Don’t make me regret this, Stark.” She warned and steadied him.

“There’s no time for alcohol when you’ve got juice pops, Danvers. I can’t hold it anymore.”

“Are you talking about the drink or do you need the bathroom?” She joked as they waited for the lyrics to start. Nobody could stand their banter for that long, but when the singing started, everyone misses it.

summary: It’s Hard Out Here for a Bitch - Lady Heroes 500/∞  Brie Larson It took me a while to realize that they’re there to help me —...
caption:
It’s Hard Out Here for a Bitch - Lady Heroes 500/∞

Brie Larson

It took me a while to realize that they’re there to help me — the voice that’s saying Don’t do that in your head, it’s actually trying to help you, to remind you of something. It’s your job to start a dialogue with it, and say, “I think I’m old enough now that I don’t need to be nervous in social situations. I really appreciate all the years you’ve spent keeping me on my toes, but I think I can go to some party, and I can feel comfortable, and I don’t need you to remind me of those fears.”
